description: Cartographic Details: Scale [1:316,800]. 1 in. = 5 mi. (W 5°--E 2°N 56°--N 50°). Relief shown by hachures. Illustration: View of the general post office London / drawn by T. Allom, engraved by H. Griffiths. Continuation inset: Scilly Islands. The contour lines are twenty feet apart on the bluffs and five feet apart on the bottom lands and river banks. The elevations of the contours above the Memphis datum are indicated by figures which are placed on the higher side of the lines to show the direction of the slopes.
Lines of benchmarks, called stone lines, are placed normal to the river at intervals of about three miles and are numbered consecutively from Cairo, Ills., northward. The benchmark is a fiat tile, 18 inches square, set about 3 feet below the surface of the ground and surmounted by a 4 inch iron pipe 4 feet long. The upper figures preceding the sign a indicate the number of the stone line and the lower figures give the number of the benchmark on the line ; the numbers following are the elevations of the tiles or pipes. Other benchmarks have their elevations indicated in a similar way.
The shore line is not reduced to the stage of the soundings, but is platted as surveyed.  Dates in the river bed indicate the days on which soundings were made.
Soundings are expressed in feet and are reduced to the mean stage of water on the days when the depths on this sheet were measured. This stage, at stone line 181 is 596.7 feet above the datum plane and the water surface has an average slope of 0-43 feet per mils, measured along the mid-bank line. A Gothie, ou plus-toft Guthie, Gut-landt en langue vul-gaire, & le pays des Gutes de Ptolemee, & la Gothifcandie, ouGothifcanZie dA-gathie. Elle a du Nordla Suede, & en partie la Norwege, dont les montagnes la bor-nent aufli du Couchant,de mefme qu'une par-tie de la Scanie,appartenante au Roy de Dane-mark, & la Mer Gothique, du Levant la Mer Balthique, ou lOoft See, qui la borne aufli du Midy, avec partie de la Scanie. Elle eft divifee en Orientale,ou Oftrogothie,pays desrenom-mezOftrogoths, Occidentale, ou Weftrego-thie, ou Weftgothie, doufortirent les Vifi-goths, &enMeridionale, ou pays de Smalan-die.  LOftrogothie comprend les pays de Tui-fthie, Bravichie, Kindme, & plusjeurs autres, avec PIfle de Gotlandt,qui eft toutefois au Roy de Danemark. La principale ville de ce pays eft Lincopen, fiege dun Evefque, dont le Dio-cefea n6 caromes.  La Weftgothie feparee de POftrogothie par le grand Lac de Vether contient la Dalie, & Vermlande du cofte du Nord feparees par le grand lac deWener, ay ant vers leMidy la Marchie, Falonie, Vasbogie, Riduegie, Fro-chinnie, Gudhemie, Cachinnie, Vartophtie,& plusjeurs autres grands pays , & Gouverne-mens, avec leurs villes, & chafteaux. La capitate ville de la Weftgothie eeft Scar, fiege dun Evefque,dont le Diocefe eft efgal en paroifles &cellede Lincopen. Ce qui rend encor confi-derablc lEvefehe de Scar eeft la ville dEls-bourg fur le rivage de la Mer,ou Pon voit tout lEfte des navires de France, dAngleterre, dEfeofle, dAllemagnq, de Danemark, & de Norwege. Allant apres de la Weftgothie au Midy Pon trouve les pays dHallandie, Scho-ningie ou Scanie, &Blechingie, fiijets a lAr-chevefque de London & au Roy de Danemark, a raifon dequoy il y a tous jours difpute entre les Goths, & les Danois, pource que les' derniers les ont ufurpes par la nonchalance des Roys de Suede. Mais laiflant ces pays 4 1Oueft, Pon trouve d PEft la Gothie Meridio-hale, ou les Smalandies, dont la principale ville-eftCaknat,des villes plus advancees vers le Sud. Dans quelques maifbns de Vermelande qui font dans les bois il fe trouve encor quelques-uns,qui adorent le feu,les forefts,& les ferpens.  Llfle dOeland, oudEland, appartenante1^ d la Gothie Meridionale, comme nen eftant fe-SPf paree que par un petit bras de mer, ou Golfe, Jj]h eft la plus belle de toutes les Ifles de la Mer Go-thique,& proche du rivage de la Moringie. Quant aux petits ils font emportez par les marcEands, pource quils ap-prennentayfementafauter, & dancer au fon du tambour, ou de la trompette, & paftent par des cercles de fer, ou de bois, ainfi que les chiens, portans par ce moyendu profit d leurs -maiftres. Gaukheihuttab/ \ _/0v \ _ CbovakL Gjers f Mmatn xO / Hornnes VDmi lid [Byglandsfjord % mK Vegusdf (I Herefoss V Arendal II ;oj PRINTED IN NORWAY BY EMIL MOESTUE cocirisc mm i m Nortk-Norway, scene photographed at midnight. truse No country in the whole wide world can offer such opportunities for rest and recreation as Norway, the {Land of the Midnight Sum. What an embarrassing choice of scenic beauty lies compressed within this country which runs through 13 degrees of latitude from 58 right up to 71 N. where, on Europes northernmost outpost, the North Cape, one stands but 19 degrees from the North Pole! Norway is not however a cold country. Indeed its climate is mild and gentle thanks to the Gulf Stream, which flows all along the coast up to the Arctic Seas, mellowing the climate to a degree more properly belonging to more southern countries. A myriad of isles along its coast forth a protective belt against the storms of the ocean and producing a channel of calm waters almost the entire length of the coast. / It is remarkable in a country with such tracts of wild nature that travelling should be both easy and pleasant. Huge sums have been expended to provide' Norway with an adequate railway system, which with its up-to-date rolling-stock, its general comfort and its mountain trains replete with sleeping, dining and observation cars are on a par with the best that is to be found anywhere in Europe. It is, however, not only to the developement of the railway traffic that special attention has been devoted, but also to that of the steamship and automobile services, and now air transport is also being organised. Norway possesses good roads and numerous and well equipped automobile routes connect outlying districts with the railways. Comfortable steamers ply on the Fjords, along the rocky coast-line to Northern Norway and to the quiet charm of South Norway. A trip by steamer along the broken and indented coast brings an ever changing panorama of new attractions. The Bergen Railway between Oslo and Bergen offers a super-abundance of scenic beauty along its track of 307 miles. The greater part of the line passes through stretches of woodland and rocks, and it is only when it ascends to the high-mountain region that its chief characteristic as a mountain railway becomes evident. This region reaches an altitude of some 4000 feet above sea level and the line runs through bleak and wild stretches of mountain across the exensive plateau known as the Hardangervidda. At the northern extremity of this are the two giant mountain masses, the Hardangerjokelen and the Hallingskarven, both covered with eternal snow and ice. Between the stations of Geilo and Mjolfjell a stretch of about 63 miles the track runs above the tree line. Previously unpopulated and very difficult of access, these mountain regions were converted by the opening of the line into a veritable Eldorado for the tourist both in summer and in winter. At the stations of Geilo, Ustaoset, Haugastol, Finse, Hallingskeid, Myrdal and Mjolfjell good hotel accommodation is available. These places are excellent resorts for short or long walking tours and also for ski-ing expeditions into the magnificent mountain scenery with which the district abounds! On the Hardangerjokelen, near Finse, one may indulge in ski-ing the whole year round. Tourists, who are either entirely unpracticed or requiring to perfect themselves in the art of ski-ing can at all times even in summer - obtain the necessary coaching in the close vicinity of their hotel. This huge'table-land is, however, particularly suited for ski-ing during the period of the {Light Winter* which extends from the month of February to the end of May. In these high-lying regions a winters day with its glowing Spring sun can be indescribably beautiful and the cold does not inconvenience one in the very least. Oslo is the capital of Norway, and the cultural as well as the commer-cial centre of Norway. The town was founded in the year 1624 by King Kristian IV and is now the largest in Norway with a population of some 300 000. Oslo may be reached by Fred. Olsen Line of Steamers from Newcastle and Antwerp; from Hull by the Ellerman Wilson Line; from Hamburg and Kiel by the Sondenfjelds-Norske Steamship Line, from Copenhagen and Stettin by the United Shipping Co., Ltd. and from New York by the Norske Amerika Line and the Skandinavien-Amerika Line. Oslo is the centre from which the whole net-work of the Norwegian Reilways radiates, moreover there are between Oslo and Sweden and the Continent of Europe several direct railway connections.. The town is delightfully situated between tre-dad hills and in open view of the fjord. Electric trains carry the visitor in 20 minutes to Holmenkollen (1000 feet above sea level) and affording glorious views. The railway continues to Frognerseteren (1500 feet above sea level), from whence an even more beautiful view across the Oslo valley and fjord is obtained. The Ekeberg hill in the eastern part of Oslo affords a closer but still glorious view across the fjord and the town itself. Quite dose to the town on the little peninsula of Bygdoy, lies a most interesting natural park containing specimens of truly southern vegetation. Here are also Bygdoy Kongsgard, the summer residence of the Royal family and the Norsk Folkemuseum with its open air theatre and restaurant. cDronningen* restaurant is the headquarters of the Royal Norwegian Yacht Club. Mention should also be made of the cKongen* restaurant, and the two Bathing Resorts cBygdo Sjobad* and cBygdSnes Bad*. Valdres has been termed {The Pearl of Norwegian Valleys*. A precious jewel indeed is .the Valdres railway, situated, as it is, in the most glorious scenic setting; a deep and broad cleft fashioned in that extensive tableland, which constitutes the middle portion of South Norway. From Oslo the line runs to Fagernes. The Valdres line is one of those most favoured by tourists; its track lies partly on the mountain side high above the dale, providing splended views across the valley and of the surrounding mountains with glimpses of well-cultivated hamlets, along-I side rushing torrents and tree-clad hills and ravines. From Fagernes, the terminus, a motoring road runs though Ostre Slidre M, - to Bygdin in the Jotunheimen while another road runs in a qiore westerly | direction through Vestre Slidre to Tyin also in the Jotunheimen, thence further across Filefjell, past Nystua and Maristova down to Lserdal at the base of the Sogne fjord. There are many places in Valdres particularly suitable for long sojourn in winter or in summer, such as the tourist hotels at Landasen, Frydenlund, Breidablik, Fagernes, Heggenes, Einang and Loken. Valdres provides one of the most beautiful and most convenient routes across the mountain ranges of East and West Norway, giving easy and speedy access to the Jotunheimen, and a veritable paradise for the rambler and also for experienced mountaineers. Jotunheimen with its wide plateaus, its towering peaks and glistening glaciers offers unbounded opportunities not only for the wanderer, who. likes to take things easy, but also for the more venturesome climber of I ripe experience. Trondheim is the railway junction and tourist centre for the northern part of the country. The town has now some 54 000 inhabitants. It was founded by King Olav Tryggvesson in 997, was at one time the capital of the whole country and is rich in memories of the past, chief among which the Domkirken (Cathedral), the most important of ecclesiastical biiildings in Scandinavia. Trondheim has particularly pleasing environs, and many of these well deserve a visit. From Trondheim daily services by comfortable steamers connect with the North of Norway, the actual region of the Midnight Sun. As the vessel wends its way through islands and reefs, the traveller finds abundant opportunity to admire a variety of scenes, the ever-changing panorama. It is more like a fairy tale than anything else when of a summers night one sees the giant wall of the Lofoten with its many peaks rising straight from the ocean as a mighty castle, and bathed in the soft glow of the midnight sun. It is surprising that even north of the Arctic Circle one frequently encounters vegetation which one generally connects with the sunny, southern lands. Well cultivated and picturesque landscapes alternate with severe Alpine scenery and throughout Nordland there is a variety of scenes, wild and smiling. Perhaps the main objective of every tourist visiting Norway is North Cape, Europes most northern outpost-jutting its brow into the icy waters of the Arctic. Here one may look towards, the unknown North; towards the silent and endless regions of ice. Proud stands that giant rock, the North Cape, washed by the waves of the Arctic Ocean; during wintertime as a sinister silhouette under the fiery glory of die Northern Lights, but during the summer a dauntless monument, as it were, beneath the flashes of colour from the midnight sun. Kristiansund is situated on three islands, washed by the seas, but well protected by the cSkjsergard*. The chief livelihood of the town is the export of dried cod and other fish products. From Kristiansund extend the beautiful fjords of the Sunndal and Surnadal and many others. The motor car ferries KristiansundKvisvik, KristiansundGimnes and KvanneRokkum connect with the road net of the rest of the country. Molde, also called the City of Roses, has an exceptionally beautiful position on the Romsdals fjord. Molde has splendid steamer services and speedy ferries connecting the inland road net, such as Angvik-Tingvoll northwards; Nsesjestranda Afarnes eastwards (On to Andalsnes) and over Vestnes in conjunction with the inland route going south. From Molde Andalsnes is reached in 21A hours by steamer. Here is the starting point of the Romsdal valley which throughout its length is flanked by mountains. Its truly magnificent scenery has made the Romsdal valley one of Norways most favoured holiday resorts. Through the valley runs the so-called cRauma Line* which provides comfortable and convenient connection between the railway net of East Norway and the Molde district. From Andalsnes there is a motor road through Romsdalen on to Dombaas, where it divides into two: one road leads through Gud-brandsdalen on to Oslo; the other across the Dovre mountains on to Trondheim. South of Molde lies Sunnmore. From Alesund, Sunnmores capital, there are excellent connections by steamer and motor to the places of interest in the district, famous for its mountain formations. North of Sogn lie Sunnfjord and Nordfjord, which towards the end of last century began to assume importance from a tourist point of view, and by reason of their great scenic beauty have now become world famous. Sunnfjord is rather milder in its aspect than Nordfjord. Therefore the traveller, if he-makes his way from the south, will encounter a panorama ever increasing in its wild grandeur, even though he confines himself to the beaten track. : The inner part of Nordfjord is perhaps most famous for its scenic charms. Here one encounters the friendly Gloppen fjord, where Sandane with its wonderful, forest-clad environs forms a happy contrast to the wilder parts of this district. At the furthest point inland at the head of the fjord lie Qlden, Loen and Yisnes in a semi-circle, surrounded by wondrous mountains and glaciers. From Olden die valley wends its way upwards to the glaciers and nature is here truly superb. Above the beautiful waters of lake Olden is the Briksdal Glacier, very easy of access. , At Loen one has the mighty mountains in close proximity. A trip up the narrow valley of Loen and across the lake is most interesting. Above lake Loen is seen the Kjendals Glacier, an arm of the Jostedals Glacier, to which there is a road. From Visnes an overland route leads to Die on the Norang fjord; another to Hellesylt; another to Merok in Geiranger and yet- another to Otta in the Gudbrandsdalen; by the latter one may travel right through to Oslo by car. On this journey one passes lake Stryn surrounded by glaciers, after which the road in mighty curves leads on past Vicjeseter; from this place one gets a glorious view across the magnificent mountain tops and glaciers of the Inner Nordfjord. The Ldlefoss Falls, tlurdan What is bound to appeal to one most in respect of the Hardanger fjord is the variety of its scenery; now awe inspiring in its wild grandeur, now friendly and smiling. The climate is soft and mild. The islands lying westwards provide shelter agpinst the sea, while the mighty moun--tains, which surround the fjord, send a light and pleasant current of air down the mountain sides to the beautiful banks below providing a refreshing effect upon the summer-heat. To travel through Hardanger is to travel through the whole of Norway as it were. Here are to be found all the characteristics of the Norwegian nature; one sees gray, stark mountains, towering proudly above picturesque, forest-clad hills and protecting many a well-cultivated farmstead. Further inland they form a circle around the fjord, imparting to it life and character. Here is a waterfall, there a glacier, offering variety and interest to the ever-changing pleasant landscape. From Odda at the head of the Sorfjord, a road leads through Telemarken, and one may also from this point take short trips to the Latefoss falls and the Buar Glacier or across the Folgefonn glacier to Mauranger (6 miles across the snow field). Eide and Ulvik, which are respectively 16 and 28 miles distant from Voss on the Bergen Railway, are the centres of interesting tours both by land and water in the Hardanger district. Another centre is Norheim-sund, also connected with the Bergen Railway by the interesting road through the wild region of the Tokagjelet to Trengereid (32 miles). From Eidf jord one of the grandest roads ever constructed leads through the Mabodal valley past Voringfossen (Fossli) across the Hardangervidda to Haugastol Station on the Bergen Railway. From Tyssedal a road leads to one of the most beautiful of ^Norway's water falls, the Skjegge-0 dalsfoss. From Sunndal there is a road across the Folgefonnen to Odda. ou) y f t ? The stave church in Hitterdal, Telemark. Telemarken is the oldest of all the Norwegian tourist regions. Long before the tourists {discovered* Gudbrandsdalen, Jotunheimen or the Fjords, travellers came to Telemark to enjoy the rich variation of nature, truly idyllic and grandiose, and also in order to cultivate acquaintance with the isolated population of that region with their distinctive national customs, attire, dances and songs. Telemarken is a most convenient and central district to which many roads give access a delightful region providing connections for the traveller to other places and districts in Norway, which are, if anything, still grander. Telemarken presents Norways nature in its most varied forms. Typical valley districts such as the Vestfjorddalen and the Grungedal, lakes such as Nordsjo and the Kviteseidvann at the upper extremity of the Bandak remind one even of the grandiose scenes of the western Fjords mountain wastes such as the Hardangervidda (north of the large lake Mosvann), peaks such as Skorve, Lifjell and Gausta (5800 feet) and waterfalls such as the Vrangfoss and the Rjukanfoss. It is difficult to imagine a more delightful excursion on a summers morning than that through the Nordsjo-Bandak Canal. From the Valley the road leads westwards across Haukeliseter to Breifonn, where it branches off in two directions; one road leading through the Bratlandsdal, so famous for its wild and rugged nature, proceeding in a southerly direction to Stavanger; the other road carries one eastwards past Seljestad to Odda in Hardanger. There are many places in Telemark suitable for a long or short stay both in winter and summer; as for instance the hotels at Tuddal, Bolke-sjo, Tinnoset, Lifjell, Sauland, Skogheim, Botn, Dalen, Bandak, Seljord, Vraliosen, Borte, Haukeliseter and Breifonn. Stavanger is a tourist centre in the West of Norway with steamshjp, rail and road connections to the most interesting scenic attractions that Norway has to offer. lit the East the mountains attract with their wild grandeur and majesty, and in this mountain wall Which stretches as far as the eye can reach, there are entrances leading to the immense plateaux and solitude of nature beyond. Fjord after fjord penetrate that huge mass of mountains, and there are islands and rocky headlands and reefs not to forget the Stavanger fjord itself {the fjord of the thousand islands*. To the South lies the Jteren, entirely separated from the coast. No islands or reefs are here found as a protection against the ocean, which in huge waves breaks upon the flat coast with its heaths, green acres and sparkling waters in a constantly changing panorama until the distant moutains bring that view to -an end. Moi near Flekkefjord (Hammerstad Tourist Hotel) is a splendid place for a stay, and at Sola in the vicinity of Stavanger there is a popular bathing resort. The Sola bay has a sandy beach nearly a mile long. From Stavanger there is practically a daily steamship service to Sauda-sjSen (Saude Tourist Hotel) and no one will ever regret having spent a stay there, or one may proceed to Sand and through the magnificent Bratlandsdal to Breifon in Roldal. Here the road branches, one direction leading westwards to Odda in the Hardanger, and the other eastwards to Telemarken. A never-to-be-forgotten excursion is that from Stavanger via Gloppedalen Dirdal and thence continuing' by steamer to the wonderful Lysefjord. Stavanger is the centre of the Norwegian canning industry and is the third largest town in Norway with about 50 000 inhabitants. Bergen, the gateway to IVestern Norway. tru. For exploring the great Fjord region of Western Norway, Bergen is an ideal centre. Bergen is connected with Newcastle by the B. & N. Line; Rotterdam and Hamburg are served by the Bergenske Dampskibsseiskab; Copenhagen by that of the Forenede Dampskibsseiskab and New York by the Norske Amerikalinje. Bergen was founded in 1070 by King Olav Kyrre and is with its 100 000 inhabitants Norways second largest town. For more than 200 years it was the chief seat of the Hanseatic League in the North as many a building still standing, bears witness. Of the many objects of which Bergen boasts one can only here make mention of the Hanseatic Museum (Hansa Merchants Office and Warehouse), the Mariakirken (Church of St. Mary the Virgin) and the Ber-genhus Fortress with the adjoining buildings of Hakonshallen and Rosen-krantz Tower, dating from the 12th and 13th centuries. For other details reference should be made to the special guide dealing with Bergen. A funicular railway ascends to the summit of the Flpif jellet (1000 feet above sea level) from which is obtained- a splended panoramic view over the town and the achipelago which surrounds it, the North Sea being visible beyond the island belt. An interesting drive may be taken through the residential quarter to Fantoft stave church, one of Norways ancient wooden churches from where magnificent views over the waters of Nordasvann are obtained. Another worth-while excursion is a motor tour through Sandviken, Kol-len, Eidsvag and Munkebotten, or by combining motor, rail and steamship services one may visit the Solstrand Hotel and Bathing Resort (some 35 kilometeres distant from the town). This tour provides magnificent views across the Bjornefjord to the Hardanger mountains with the Folgefonnen glacier visible in the distance. The Dovre railway is, with the exception of the Bergen line, the grandest of all the Norwegian railways although there are those who prefer the Dovre line, because of its endless mountain wastes and the open outlook compared with the wild mountain formations which the Bergens-line has to offer. Also a considerable portion of the Dovreline lies over vast and bleak mountain stretches with a view of glaciers and giant mountain tops. From Oslo the track leads through large fertile fields of the Ostlandet and alongside lake Mjiisa, past Hamar (Hosbjor) to Lillehammer, whose many hotels attract tourists from every corner of Europe. And thence further up through the Gudbrandsdalen the train wends is way past the well-known sanatoria and tourist hotels of Austlid, Bauker, Gausdal, Tofte, Winge, Gola, Fefor and many others until one reaches Otta, whence the automobile route links up Geiranger and Nordfjord. Through the well tilled acres and large forests of the Gudbrandsdalen the train continues to the mountain region of Dombas, 2000 feet above sea level, where the line branches off into two directions the one, the Rauma line going on to Andalsnes in the Romsdalen, while the other the Dovre line makes it way across the Dovre mountains to Trondheim. At the stations of Dombas, Fokstua, Hjerkinn, Kongsvoll, Drivstua and Opdal there are good hotels and mountain hospices, conveniently situated for shorter or longer walking tours and ski-ing expeditions. Some of these mountain hotels on the Dovre mountains and in the Driva Valley were erected by the state in the beginning of the 11th century and have thus welcomed guests for as long as 900 years! The Naero fjord, Sogn. tPiUe A visit to the Sogne fjord is undoubtedly one of the most delightful experiences one can wish for. From Vadheim there is an inland route (75 miles) through the beautiful and majestic region of the Sunnfjord right on to Sandane in Nordfjord. Beyond Vadheim stands the famous resort of Balestrand (Bal-holm), visited by summer guests from all parts of the world. Here one arm of the fjord extends northwards to Fjasrland with. the glaciers of Boyums and Supphelle; the latter can be reached by motor, the journey taking only half au hour. Another arm- of the fjord brings one to Sogndal, whence there is an interesting drive to Marifjora and up die Jostedal vaHey. ' ' . - Further along the main fjord are the Aurlands fjord and the Naero fjord giving access to Flam and Gudvangen. Both these fjords, particularly the latter, are surrounded by mighty mountain ranges, their summits ranging from 5500 to 6500 feet, and the fjord being quite narrow one receives the impression that the steep mountains are almost closing in on one. From Gudvangen at the head of the Naero fjord there is a road through the narrow and wild Naerodal to Stalheim and on to Voss. From Flam at the extreme end of the Aurlands fjord there is a road up the mighty Flam valley ascending in zig-zags to Vatnahalsen and Myrdal. - From Laerdal a good motor road runs across the Filefjell past Mari-slova and Nystua to Tyin in the Jotunheimen and to Fagernes in Valdres. From Maristova there is a road through Hemsedalen to Gol on the Oslo -Bergen railway. Beyond Ardal is the Vettisfoss, the highest waterfall in the north of Europe (800 feet) and from Skjolden there is a road to Turtagro at the entrance to the mighty mountain expanses of the Jotunheimen. Brekkesto on the South coast of Norway. trusts In contrast to the nature in its wild state as one finds it in Western Norway and in the Nordland, the characteristic feature of the Sorland is one of uniformity and mildness, and compared with the prospering farms of the Ostland one finds in the Sorland a very scattered population, with farmsteads in tranquil bays or in narrow, but often idyllic and well-cultivated hollows. The rocky coastline of the Sorland with its thousands of islands constitutes a natural shelter from the open sea. Seen from a distance it appears bleak and banen, but getting nearer one perceives some of the most superb landscapes, rich in vegetation and resplendant with wooded hills. The Setesdal is, in many respects, one of the most interesting valleys in Norway; no other part of the country has, to a greater extent, retained the traditional and national characteristics of its customs, dress and language and even mentality. These distinguishing characteristics have made the Setesdal famous, but since the opening of the Setesdal Railway one must travel further up into the valley in order now to encounter those characeristics which are a result of the isolation and lack of outside influence, to which the valley was for so long subjected. From Kristiansand the railway runs to the Byglandsfjord; thence there is a motor route 90 miles in length up the valley to Hovden Turisthytte, from where there is very convenient mountain pass over to Telemark. From Arendal there is a motor route to Saetersdalens Summer Home at Setesdal and a railway to Tveitsund at the southern extremity of lake Nisser, which one can traverse by steamer, but there is also a road for vehicles along the shores of the lake. From the northern extremity there is -a motor road to Kviteseid on the road between Skien and Telemark.

THE VICEROYALTY OF EGYPT—No. II.
Inhabitants, Races, etc.—Of the inhabitants of Egypt, the great majority—those of the peasant class or Fellahs, as they are called—are undoubtedly indigenous, and may be regarded as descendants of the ancient Egyptians. These having embraced Mohammedanism, are now generally denominated Arabs, though easily distinguished from the true Arab, who invariably regards the Fellah with contempt. The Copts are the Egyptians who still cling to the Christian faith; though comparatively few, they contrive to hold a respectable position in society by means of their education and useful talents. They are thus widely separated by their faith and social lot from the Fellahs, though of kindred race with them. The Fellahs are generally peasants and laborers ; the Copts fill the posts of clerks and accountants. With these aboriginal Egyptians are mingled, in various proportions, Turks, Arabs (chiefly Bedouins), Armenians, Greeks, Berbers, Negroes, Jews, and Franks. The Turks form a privileged class, or kind of aristocracy, and hold the principal offices under government. The Arab tribes considered as belonging to Egypt, and to whom lands have been assigned, are the Bedouins, who supply the country with camels, sheep, and to some extent with horses. Their haunts are on the borders of El-Fay-oum; their numbers about 250,000. The Armenians are generally bankers or jewelers ; the Greeks are all merchants and traders. The Berbers, from Lower Nubia, below the second cataract, do all porters7 work, while the negroes are preferred as domestic servants. The whole population of Egypt has been estimated by the government, from apparently ample data, at three and a half or nearly four millions; but the Europeans, who have examined this question on the spot, concur in reducing the estimate to two and a half millions; the Fellahs being nearly 2.000,000; the Copts 145,000; and the ruling caste of Turks and Mamelukes (that is, slaves chiefly from Caucasus, taken young, and reared as Turks), not above 20,000.
Government.—The government of Egypt being in the hands of Turks, is, as might be expected, an unqualified despotism. Under the first viceroy, and founder of the present dynasty, Mohammed All, it became in practice more enlightened, liberal, and humane ; but its simple fundamental principles remain unchanged. He commenced his great reformations in 1808 by abolishing the right of private individuals to hold estates in land. Thus he became the proprietor of the whole kingdom (houses and gardens excepted), and found himself in a position to carry out his schemes of improvement. He then divided and subdivided the whole country, the officers of every grade, down to the Sheik-el-Belid or village chief, being not merely magistrates, but overseers of work and tax-gatherers. The Fellahs received wages, sowed their fields as they were ordered by the government, carried their produce to the government stores, and were paid for it at the government price. Thus Mohammed Ali took into his own hands all the agriculture, as well as all the manufactures of the kingdom. He aimed at developing the resources of Egypt, but he never dreamed of turning to account the mainspring of national prosperity, namely, the untiring energy with which every man labors to promote his own welfare. To foster this spirit is to make a nation rich. But the prosperity which Mohammed Ali had in view was that of his own treasury, and not that of his people. He aimed at being the sole farmer, manufacturer, and merchant in his dominion; and to his subjects, who were reduced to abject slavery, and heavily taxed, lie left but a wretched subsistence. All the reforms effected by Mohammed Ali, his schools, manufactures, canals, plantations, well-appointed army, and increasing navy, all tended toward the organization of a system on which he reckoned for the increase of his financial means and political power; but as to the instruction or well-being of his people in general, nothing could be farther from his thoughts. The people were reduced by him to the deepest distress, while he certainly amassed no treasures.
National Finances.—The revenues of Egypt are derived from various sources, the chief being the miri or land tax, for which the districts are answerable, however individuals may fail, so that the government is sure to be paid. This yields nearly half of the whole revenue. Next in importance are the proceeds of monopolies, namely, of cotton, indigo, sugar, rice, opium, etc. Then come the capitation, the customs, taxes on grain brought to market, on cattle slaughtered, on date-trees, fishing, etc.; in all producing about $12,500,000.
Armed Forces.—The Egyptian army is composed of 130,000 regular troops, 12,000 of whom are cavalry, and of about 40,000 national guards. To these may be added about 40,000 irregular cavalry (Bedouins, chiefly in Arabia). The fleet consists of 10 or 11 ships of the line, six frigates,
and a dozen smaller vessels : connected with it and with the arsenals is
✓
a force or 40,000 men. Thus the forces maintained by a prince whose revenues hardly exceed twelve millions and a half, can not altogether fall much short of 270,000 men. The officers, those of high rank especially, experience liberal treatment, while the men, who have been for the most part forced into service by conscription, are miserably paid.
Agriculture.—As soon as the waters have retired, the Egyptians sow their wheat and barley, which are quite ripe in May, in the Delta, where the produce of the field arrives at maturity generally a month later than in Upper Egypt. Durrah (sorghum vulgare), the grain on which the natives chiefly subsist, and millet, are sown later and gathered earlier. Of maize, two crops are often raised in the year. Rice, the sale of which is a monopoly of the government, is a novelty to the Egyptian husbandman, and is grown chiefly in the low grounds near Rosetta and Damietta. Beans, lupins, lentils, and various kinds of pulse, with onions, bamieh (hybiscus esculentus), and mallow are cultivated and consumed in great quantities. The system of husbandry is probably the same now as it was 3,000 years ago, wherever the government has not interfered with it, by introducing new' objects of culture. The Egyptian peasant is extremely tenacious of ancient usages ; his plough at the present day exactly resembles that figured in the hieroglyphics; for a harrow, he uses a roller made of a piece of the trunk , of a palm-tree ; and he allows no rest to the inundated land, but relieves it only by change of crops. The efforts of the government, howrever, to increase the commercial resources of the country, have disturbed the traditional routine. The cultivation of cotton, begun in 1821, has now extended widely; indigo succeeds in the Fay-oum and Upper Egypt. The growth of the sugar-cane is confined to the latter country, the manufacture of the sugar being carried on at Minyeh. For the sake of the silk manufacture, millions of mulberry trees have been planted in Egypt. The cultivation of the olive, also, is now encouraged; and attempts have been made even to naturalize the coffee-plant, clove, and cinnamon.
Manufactures, etc.—The Egyptians still adhere to their ancient custom of uniting the followers of each business or profession ink \ guild or corporation, governed by their chief or sheikh, who acts, if n_ed be, as their representative. These guilds are exceedingly numerous, as might be expected among a people whose social organization reaches to a remote antiquity. Of all these trades, however, very few claim especial mention on the score of importance or singularity. Among these few we must place the business of the mahm-al-farujy or egg-hatching establishments, at which twenty-four millions of eggs are submitted annually to the vivifying ovens. The business of tanning, also, is one in which the Egyptians succeed perfectly by a process peculiar to themselves. They make excellent morocco leather, which is goatskin dressed and dyed in a particular manner. The pottery of Egypt, also,
deserves a word of praise, chiefly for the merit of the bardaks or water-jars. The best bardaks are those made at Kenneh, which, besides being impregnated with a fine and lasting perfume, are, in various degrees and forms, permeable to water; so that while some serve as filters, others exude the purified fluid and keep it cool by evaporation, which effect, in such a climate as Egypt, is a matter of great importance. These jars are transmitted to Cairo in a singular manner. They are tied together in large numbers, with their mouths downward, and thus forming long rafts, are floated down the Nile. But w'hat may be called indigenous industry, though it could claim a long list of trades and occupations, is too rude and primitive to supply the wants of the country under the new system of things. The manufactures on a large scale in Egypt which are carried on with skill and capital, and the aid of machinery, all owe their establishment to the late Mohammed Ali, and are, in fact, the property of the government. That energetic ruler had incautiously embraced the doctrine that it is always more advantageous to produce than to purchase, and consequently he sought to supply all the wants of the country from within, imagining that every branch of industry •which flourished elsewhere would prove profitable in Egypt also. He established above 20 cotton mills on a large scale, horses or oxen being employed as the moving power. His linen manufactories deliver annually 3,000,000 pieces, and compete in Italy with those of Germany and England. The manufacture of silk, as well as the rearing of the silk-worm, received from him a powerful impulse. Then woolen cloth, hempen cordage, sugar, indigo, oil, gunpowder, and various chemical products, all engaged his attention; and in every case he established manufactories, to be conducted on the public account. He even went so far as to establish an iron-foundery at Boulac, a suburb of Cairo, on the Nile. This experiment, made on a handsome scale in a country not affording either iron ore or fuel, and where machinery is soon destroyed by the fine sand and the corrosion of the atmosphere (owing, perhaps, to the presence of carbonic acid), must necessarily have proved a serious loss. His establishments for the manufacture of fire-arms, and of military accoutrements in general, merit commendation on grounds of policy, if those of economy be insufficient.
Trade and Commerce.—The trade of Egypt with European states has its seat at Alexandria. The exports consist principally of raw native produce and merchandise brought by caravans from the interior of Africa: cotton, beans, peas, rice, wheat, barley, flax, hides, etc., being the chief native exports ; and ivory, gold-dust, gums, ostrich feathers, etc., those from the interior. The imports from European states consist chiefly of manufactured goods of all sorts, machinery, coals, iron and iron ware, cloths, liquors, sugar, etc. The total values of the imports and exports, according to the custom-house reports for the years 1842, 1846, and 1851, five years apart, were:
Imports 1842.....................$12,354,366
“	1846	  8.750.692
“	1851	  10,967,039
Exports 1842...........................$9,024,830
“	1846.......................... 9.508.211
“	1851......................... 16,171,245
The states having the principal share in this trade are England, Austria, France, Tuscany, G reece, Turkey, Syria, etc. The chief commercial relations with Arabia and India are carried on by Cosseir and Suez, and since the establishment of regular steam-packets on the Mediterranean and Indian seas, Egypt has become the route between England and its Eastern possessions. To facilitate the land transit from sea to sea, a railroad, 120 miles long, has been constructed between Alexandria and Cairo, and will soon be completed between the latter place and Suez. It is also proposed to excavate a ship-canal across the Isthmus of Suez. These works may again render Egypt the great entrepot of commerce between the Eastern and the Western worlds.
Principal Towns.—The only towns of Egypt which demand notice in this connection are Cairo, Alexandria, Damietta, Rosetta, etc. The smaller towns have little external interest except so far as relates to their antiquities and works of art, which are elsewhere mentioned.
Cairo (El-Kahireh), the capital and seat of government, is built near the right bank of the Nile, and about five miles from the origin of its Delta, lat. 30° 2', and long. 31° 16/; elevation 41 feet above sea-level. The city proper is built on a slope at the foot of one of the lowest ridges of Jebel Mokkatam, and occupies an area of about three square miles. It is surrounded by old walls, and the highest part of the ridge is crowned by a citadel which contains the palace of the viceroy, the arsenal, mint, and public offices. The citadel is commanded by forts placed on the extremity of the chain of Mokkatam. The suburbs Boulac and Misr-el-Aatik are separated from the city proper by a series of gardens and plantations. Cairo is divided into several distinct quarters according to the religion and race of its inhabitants, and these are separated by gates. The streets are crooked, narrow, and ill-paved; but there are many squares, and the dwellings are generally substantial. The remarkable edifices of Cairo comprise many of the finest remains of Arabian architecture; among them are between 300 and 400 mosques, several ancient gates, an aqueduct for conveying water from the Nile to the citadel, the ancient works of the citadel, and the palace and well of Joseph. At old Cairo are the seven towers, still called the u granary of Joseph,77 and serving their ancient purpose. In the island of Rodah is the celebrated Nilometer, a graduated column for indicating the height of the water during the flooding of the river. Numerous ancient cisterns and baths still ornament the city. On the south, outside the walls, are the celebrated tombs of the Mamelukes, and on the north-east the obelisk of Heliopolis. Among the modern edifices, the only two of consequence are the new palace, with extensive gardens on the Nile, between Boulac and old Cairo, and the handsome residence of the viceroy at Shoubra. In the city are several schools, a museum of antiquities, a magnetic observatory, several hospitals, etc. Cairo was long the chief entrepot for the commerce of Egypt, but its trade has much declined. It has, however, many extensive manufactures: cotton-spinning mills, iron founderies, bleacheries, etc. Boulac, a mile north-west, is the port of Cairo, and here all vessels navigating the river load and unload their cargoes. Around it are numerous residences of grandees. Cairo was founded by the Arabs about 970. Population 300,000.
Alexandria (Iskenderyeh), near the westernmost branch of the Nile on the Mediterranean, is the principal sea-port, lat. 31° 12x, and long. 29° 53', 120 miles north-west Cairo, with which it communicates by railroad, the Mahmudiyeh Canal, and the Nile. The modern city is built on a peninsula (anciently the island of Pharos), and the isthmus connecting it with the continent. Alexandria is generally a well-built city, and in its newer parts has more of a European than an Asiatic or African aspect. The principal buildings and institutions are the new palace, a large naval arsenal, the naval and military hospital, custom-house, tribunal of commerce, school of instruction, and medical, naval, and other schools. A castle called Farillon replaces the famous u Pharos77 of antiquity. Alexandria has two ports, occupying the opposite sides of the isthmus ; in the western and best, ships anchor in from 22 to 40 feet water. It is the principal commercial entrepot of Egypt, and an important station on the overland route between Europe and India. Population 66,000, of which about 10,000 are employed in the garrisons and arsenal. The ancient city was built on the mainland, where its ruins cover a vast extent of surface. It was founded by Alexander the Great in 322 B. c. Two granite obelisks, called Cleopatra7s Needles, still remain entire.
Damietta) on the east branch of the Nile, eight miles from its mouth,
is generally a meanly built town, but has some good mosques, baths, etc. Its harbor is bad, and its commerce has mostly been transferred to Alexandria, and at the present day consists of little more than a coasting and river trade. Population 28,000. Rosetta, on the west branch, is pleasantly situated and neatly built, and has still a thriving general trade and some manufactures, but since the opening of the canal between Alexandria and Cairo, its importance and population have greatly decreased. Population 6,000. Suez, at the head of the gulf of the same name, is a frontier sea-port, and from its position on the high road between the East and West, has always been a place of extensive transit trade. It is a wretched town, however, and so inferior is its port, that steamers are obliged to moor two miles from the town.
Monumental History.—Passing over the years during which Egypt was ruled by gods and demigods, we come to the mortal Menes, the founder of the first of 30 dynasties, recorded more or less perfectly by Manetho, the high-priest of Isis who lived about 300 b. c. But so arbitrarily has the high-priest’s information been dealt with, that we can not decide whether he places Menes 5,400 or 3.900 years before the Christian era. However, it is worthy of remark, that the son and successor of Menes is said to have written a book on anatomy, and to have had a temple at Memphis. This city was already, under the second dynasty, the capital of the kingdom. With the fourth dynasty begins the period of undoubted cotemporary monuments. Shufo (Cheops) built the great pyramid, in which his name is written; his immediate successor built the second; and his nephew, Menkare, the third. A portion of the coffin of Menkare, with his name inscribed on it. is now in the British Museum, being probably the oldest specimen of writing extant beyond the pyramids and the tombs of Gizeh and Sakkara. These earliest known specimens of hieroglyphic writing exhibit the art in complete maturity, and, coupled with the pyramids, prove that Egypt, under the fourth dynasty, was already far advanced beyond the infancy of civilization. The eleventh dynasty was the first of the Diospolitan or Theban kings, whose celebrity, however, commenced with the twelfth, to which belonged Sesortasen, one of those kings whose achievements have been heaped on the half-fabulous Sesostris ; and of whom there remains an inscribed pillar recording liis conquests in Nubia, and his son Amme-nemes III., who embanked Lake Moeris and built the labyrinth. This edifice, the foundations of which maybe still traced, appeared to the Greeks, even wrhile Karnak stood in all its glory, to be the greatest and most -wonderful in the world. The memorials of this distinguished dynasty are written or graven on the walls in the grottoes of Beni Hassen. The fifteenth and two succeeding dynasties were those of the Hyksos or shepherds, whose tyrannous rule continued for some centuries. These shepherds, that is, pastoral, and comparatively rude tribes, appear to have been the Caimanites, who, on their expulsion from Egypt, founded Jerusalem. With the eighteenth dynasty begins the most brilliant period of Egyptian history and the greatness of Thebes. Aahmes (Amosis), the first king of the eighteenth dynasty, is supposed by some to have been the Pharaoh (Ph-re, king), under whom the Exodus took place; though others suppose the Exouus to have taken place in the reign of Ramses (Sesostris), the last king, or last but one of this dynasty. Subsequently comes a series of great princes—Amenoph, Thothmes, Horus, Ramses, and Menephthah, to whom are due the grand monuments of Karnak, Luxor (el-Akhsar), Medinet Abu, Amada, Semneh, etc. The inscriptions of these victorious kings are found at the present day from Syria (at the Nahr-el-Celb) to Jebel Barkal, above Dongola in Nubia. Their conquests are recounted on obelisks, temples, tombs, and represented by paintings, with hieroglyphic explanations, so elaborate and frequent as to furnish the material of a voluminous, though still obscure literature. The tombs of the twelfth dynasty are, many of them, in the valley named Biban-el-Muluk (Gates of the Kings), extending in subterranean chambers, with painted or inscribed walls, to a distance, in some instances, of 350 feet. Some papyri, written in the reign of Menephthah II., the last of this dynasty, have been partially interpreted, and throw a curious light on the manners of the age. One of them contains instructions written by a minister of state for the secret preparation of a certain feast, whence it appears that the Ethiopian feast entitled, “ Table of the Sun77 (in old Egyptian phrase, the king), as described by Herodotus 800 years later, had its origin in Thebes. Under the twentieth dynasty began the decline of Egypt and of Egyptian art, while Assyria, on the other hand, now rose. A Pharaoh, probably the last of the twenty-first dynasty (Tanites, by Tsaiah sailed the princes of Zoan), gave his daughter in marriage to King Solomon (1 Kings ix. 16). The twenty-second began with Sesonchis, the Shishak of Scripture (the first Pharaoh mentioned by name in the sacred volume), to whom Jeroboam fled, and who afterward sacked Jerusalem. In the paintings at Karnak, which represent his conquests, this event is shown in detail, and the written title, u King of the Jews,77 points out the principal captive. The next dynasty was founded by Sabaco (So, the ally of Hosea 2 Kings xvii. 4), originally from Upper Nubia. His name, as well as that of his follower Tirhaka or Zeracli the Ethiopian, is found on the monuments. The twenty-sixth dynasty is distinguished chiefly by Psammetichus, in whose reign the Greeks began to grow numerous in Egypt. This was followed by the Persian Cambyses and his successors for 124 years, after which period we have again three dynasties of native princes, the last king of Egyptian race being Nectanebus, of whom there remains a temple and inscription at Philse. He was driven from the throne in 841 b. c. by a usurper, who was soon after displaced by Darius Ochus; and he in turn in 332 b. c. by Alexander.
Modern History.—In a. d. 639 the Arabs effected the conquest of Egypt, which, under the Mohammedan rulers, soon became totally metamorphosed, at least in spirit. In the great monuments of the ancient Pharaohs the followers of the Caliphs saw nothing but the work of Jins. In 1250 the government was seized by the Mamelukes (slaves chiefly from Caucasus, bred to military service), who had grown into power by the favor of Saladin. These were subdued by Selim, the Ottoman Sultan, in 1520; but the descendants of the defeated chiefs kept the country in disorder for more than two centuries, and when, in the first half of the eighteenth century, the Ottoman Empire was hard pressed by Russia and Austria, Egypt fell again under the turbulent sway of the Mamelukes, who continued to retain the sovereign power during the French invasion in 1798 ; but on the expulsion of the French by the British forces, the Ottoman Porte effectually urged its claim to sovereignty, and the young officer commanding the Turkish forces, Mohammed Ali Bey, contrived to shorten the contest by entrapping and treacherously murdering the Mameluke leaders. Such was the act which founded the fortunes of the future pacha. As he consolidated his power in Egypt, the Porte, with sinister intentions probably, commanded him to suppress the Wahabees. a fanatical sect in Arabia, grown formidable by their numbers and audacity. But his energy and perseverance overcame all difficulties. He subdued the Wahabees, and annexed to his dominions all the provinces of Arabia bordering on the Red Sea. On the banks of the Nile his conquests extended to Sennaar and Kordofan. At length he broke openly with the Porfe, and the Ottoman and Egyptian forces meeting in the plains of Nizib, in Syria, in June, 1839, the latter gained a decisive victory; the result of which was a treaty confirming to Mohammed Ali the viceroyalty of Egypt as a fief of the Ottoman Empire, hereditary in his family.

CAPE
GOOD HOPE-CAPE C0L0IY.
Astronomical Position.—Between latitudes 28° 127 and 34° 48/south, and longitudes 16° 247 and 28° 42/ east from Greenwich, or 93° 26/ and 105° 447 from Washington.
Boundaries.—Northern: the Gariep or Orange River ;—north-eastern: the Nu-Gariep, the southern branch of the Gariep ;—eastci'n: the Welge Spruit River, the Wittebergen and Stormbergen mountains, the White and Black Kei rivers, the Klaas Smits River, the Chumie and the Keis-kamma; and—southern and western: the Atlantic Ocean.
Dimensions.—The length of the territory thus bounded, east and west, is about 620 miles, and its greatest breadth, north and south, 435 miles. The area is estimated at 110.256 square miles.
Coasts, Headlands, Bays, etc.—The coast-line of the Colony has an extent of about 1,200 miles. The north-west portion, lying considerably out of the tract which is usually navigated, is imperfectly known, but is understood to consist of sandy plains, generally covered with shrubby plants. To the south-west and south it loses this character, and though seldom forming what may be called a bold and rocky coast, presents an almost uninterrupted series of headlands and indentations. The former occasionally stretch out into lofty promontories, the principal of which are the celebrated Cape of Good Hope, forming the extremity of the isolated mountain mass, of which Table Mount is the culminating point, and Cape Agulhas the most southern point of Africa. The latter are often scooped out into capacious bays, which have ample depth of water, but lying exposed in some direction or other, are very imperfect roadsteads. The chief of these bays are, on the west, St. Helena Bay, Sal-danha Bay, and Table Bay; and on the south False Bay, with its important arm called Simon’s Bay, St. Sebastian’s Bay, Mossel Bay, the Camtoos, and Algoa Bay. Among these complete shelter is afforded only by Saldanha Bay, which possesses all the essentials of an excellent harbor; and Simon’s Bay, which has been selected for the arsenal and chief naval station of the Colony.
Physical Aspect of the Interior.—The interior of the country may be described as consisting generally of a succession of plateaux and mount-which rise above each other, and increase in elevation as
am ranges,
they recede from the coast, each range.forming the boundary of a lower and the abutment of the next higher plateau ; and again lowering down considerably toward the Gariep or Orange River. Beginning in the west, the first mountain range is the Bokkeveld, which lies about 40 miles inland, and stretches from north to south, in a direction nearly parallel with the west coast, till it reaches the neighborhood of the town of Worcester, latitude 33° 407 south. Almost parallel to this range, but about 100 miles farther inland, is the Rogge veld. Between these ranges lies an extensive elevated plateau, which, according to its proximity to either range, takes the name of the Bokkeveld or of the Roggeveld Karroo. In like manner several mountain ranges run parallel with the south coast. The first and lowest stretches from west to east, without interruption, for about 200 miles, leaving a belt along the coast which seldom exceeds 20 miles. This range of hills connects with the Bokkeveld. and properly forming one of its branches, takes, in the different localities through which it passes, the names of the Zwellendam, the Outeniqua, and the Zitzikarnme mountains. Behind it, and at a distance varying from 15 to 30 miles, is a second range, connected likewise with the Bokkeveld, so as to form another of its branches, and known by the name of the Zwarte or Black Mountains. Between these two eastern ranges lie the plateaux of Kannaland and Long Kloof. About 70 miles behind the Black Mountains is the last great eastern range, which links with the Roggeveld, near latitude 32° 107 south, and takes in succession the names of the Klein Roggeveld. the Nieuwveld, and the Sneeuw or Snowy mountains, the last forming the highest mountain chain in South Africa, and attaining a height which has been variously estimated, but probably is not less than 10,000 feet. The large space between this range and the Black Mountains is occupied by a plateau, called the Great Karroo. On the west it connects with the Bokkeveld and the Roggeveld Karroos, and on the east with a similar tract called Candeboo, and thus the whole of these united Karroos may be regarded as one immense plateau, raised, on an average, 3.000 feet above the level of the sea, surrounded on all
sides by mountain ranges, and stretching continuously,
varying width, for 500 miles.
though
with
Geology.—The geological structure of the mountains appears to be very uniform.. They have a nucleus of granite, which sometimes comes to the surface, and forms the predominating rock, but much more frequently the granite is overlain by enormous masses of sandstone, easily distinguished by the numerous pebbles of quartz which are imbedded in it. The mountain summit, when composed of granite, is usually round and smooth, but when composed of the quartzose sandstone is often perfectly flat, and assumes the form of which Table Mount is a well-known specimen. The thickness of this stratum in some localities is not less than 2,000 feet, and may then be seen forming steep mural faces resembling masonry, or exhibiting a series of salient angles and indentations as sharp, regular, and well defined as if they had been chiseled. With the granite are often associated primitive schists, the decomposition of which seems to have furnished the chief ingredients of the thin barren clay which forms the characteristic covering of the Karroos. In some places, particularly toward the south coast, more recent formations appear, and limestone is frequently seen piercing the surface.
Rivers, etc.—Notwithstanding its lofty mountain ranges and elevated plateaux, Cape Colony has scarcely any navigable rivers. Elephant or Olifant’s River, which falls into the Atlantic in the west of Clanwilliam division, is affected by the tide, and is navigable for boats for 30 miles, but, like almost all the other rivers of the Colony, is encumbered at its mouth by a bar, over which no ordinary sailing vessel can lloat. On the south coast the Breede, which empties itself into St. Sebastian’s Bay, in Zwellendam division, admits vessels of 200 tons into the port of Beaufort, which stands at its mouth, but immediately thereafter becomes nav-* igable only by small craft. To judge by the map, one might be apt to suppose that the Colony was remarkably well supplied with water. Streams are there seen traversing it in all directions, some of them apparently receiving numerous tributaries, and running a course of several hundred miles; and the fact is, that at the season when rain prevails, many of them are swollen into rivers of great width, and of a depth which would float the largest vessel in safety. But the fall of these rivers is as rapid as their rise had been, and the rains have no sooner ceased than they either disappear altogether or sink down into deep chasms, and occupy a shallow rocky bed, overhung on both sides by lofty precipices of the prevailing sandstone. They thus not only become useless as a means of internal traffic, but can not even be made available for purposes of irrigation.
Climate.—The temperature of the Colony varies much in different localities, but its general average may be stated at 67^° at Cape Town, that of the coldest month being 57° and that of the hottest 79° Fahr. The extremes, however, have a much wider range. In the mountainous districts snow covers the highest summits during half the year, and the temperature, cooled down by the blasts which descend from them, often falls below freezing. The alternations of heat and cold are frequently great, as well as sudden. The south-east wind sometimes blows with all the characteristics of a simoon. This wind, disagreeable though it be, is regarded as not prejudicial to health, and the statistics of the Colony certainly go to prove that there are few climates in which, under
ordinary circumstances, human life is more likely to run its fullest course. Less rain falls in the interior, and on the west coast of Cape Colony, than in any other part of the world, excepting rainless districts.
Vegetation.—The vegetation of the Cape is of a peculiar and distinctive character. To this, however, there are some curious exceptions in the case of particular plants, where a connection manifests itself between the botany of this part of the world and that of very remote countries. Yet nowhere else are genera and species confined within narrower limits than here, without any apparent cause for a dispersion so arbitrary. In many respects the vegetation in the eastern districts of the Colony differs widely from that on the west, although several plants are common to both. With the exception of the silver-tree or witteboom (leucadendron argen-teum), none of the indigenous trees in the vicinity of Cape Town attain any considerable size. But the characteristic vegetation of the Colony consists in its ericoe or heaths, stapeliae or carrion flowers, and proteacete ; of the first, there are about 400 species, and of the last 200, all exceedingly beautiful, but having a range so limited that none are to be seen north of the mountains which bound the Great Karroo, while by far the greatest number grow within 100 miles of Cape Town; the protea cynaroides, bearing a flower the size of a man’s hat, is found on Table Mountain; as for the singular and fleshy stapelias, resembling a starfish, about 100 species are mentioned, but they are almost entirely confined to the dry and sandy regions of the western coast, where they cover a tract of many degrees of latitude in extent. A great portion of the eastern frontier of the Colony and the adjacent districts are covered with extensive thickets of a strong succulent and thorny vegetation, called by the natives the bush. The most common plants of the bush are aloes, of many species, all exceedingly fleshy, and some beautiful; the great red-flowering arborescent aloe, and some others, make a conspicuous, though by no means graceful, figure in the eastern part of the Colony, where they grow irregularly scattered over the parched and naked faces of the hills. Other characteristic plants of the eastern districts are the spekboom (pork-tree—-portulacaria afra), schotia speciosa, calitris or cedar, two or three species of podocarpus or yellow-wood, and the great succulent euphorbias, which grow into trees 40 feet high, branching like a candelabrum, entirely leafless, prickly, and with a very acrid juice : the euphorbia meloformis, three feet in diameter, lies on the ground, to which it is attached by slender fibrous roots, and is confined to the mountains of Graaf-Reynet, where also is found the extraordinary testudinaria or Hottentot’s bread. The encephalartos, of which there are 15 species, all having the appearance of dwarf-palms, but without any similarity of structure, scarcely occur in the Cape Colony, properly so called, but extend over the mountains of Kaffraria, Tambooka, and Delagoa Bay, almost to the tropics. The brilliant strelitzias are almost peculiar to the districts of George and Zwellendam. Throughout are found various species of acacia, many beautiful ones of oxalis, innumerable species of ixia, gladiolus, tritonia, watsonia, hesperanthera, and other handsome iridacese, known by the name of Cape bulbs; nor ought we to omit the endless varieties ^f pelargonium or Cape geranium, gnaphalium, xeran-themum, diosma, mesembryanthemum or fig-marigold, shrubby boragi-nacese, and curious, if not large or showy, blossomed orchidacese.
Animals.—The animals indigenous to this Colony are almost endlessly varied, from the most unwieldy bulks to the most delicate and graceful forms. Among quadrupeds may be enumerated the giraffe, elephant, rhinoceros, the hippopotamus, now much less frequently seen than formerly ; the lion, panther, hyena, jackal, wolf, wild boar, quagga, buffalo, antelope, springbok, monkey, porcupine, ant-eater, etc. Among birds are the ostrich, eagle, vulture, pelican, flamingo, crane, guinea fowl, turtle-dove, and smaller species in great variety. The reptiles include among their number the largest and most venomous of their class, including the boa constrictor and the cobra da capello. In the surrounding seas and along the coasts whales and seals exist in such numbers as to make the capture of them an important occupation, while both there and in the rivers there is no deficiency of smaller fish.
Aborigines.—The original inhabitants of the peninsula of Southern Africa consist of two distinct negro races—the Hottentot and the Kafir, which are again subdivided into 10 or 12 different tribes. The Hottentots occupy the northern portion of the peninsula and the Kafirs the northeastern. The first are a mild and timid people, with some talent but no energy. They make excellent shepherds and herdsmen, and are faithful and honest. When young they are clean limbed and well proportioned, complexion a clear olive, cheek-bones high and prominent, teeth small and exquisitely enameled. The Kafirs are a remarkably handsome race, tall, stout, beautifully formed, and graceful in their movements, cheerful and contented expression of countenance, complexion verging toward black. The offshoots of these two great families are the Korannas or Koras, the Bojesmans or Bushmen, Namaquas, Damaras, Griquas, Bechuanas, Mantatas, and Zoolahs.
Civil Divisions, Population, etc.—For administrative purposes the Colony is divided into two provinces, and these are subdivided into districts, as follows :
Western Province.—Cape, Stellenbosch, Zwellendam, Caledon, Worcester, Clanwilliam, Paarl, Malmesbury, George, Beaufort.
Eastern Province.—Uitenhage, Port Elizabeth, Graaf-Reynet, Cra-dock, Colesberg, Somerset, Albany, Fort Beaufort, Victoria and Albert.
The population of the Colony, according to the census of 1851, was 285,279, of which nearly one-half belonged to the colored races and the remainder all Europeans or of European descent. In both cases the male greatly exceeds the female population.
Soil, Agriculture, etc.—The temperature is apparently such as ought to favor the growth of all the ordinary cereals; but even where the soil is well adapted for their growth, it often proves most unpropitious. Long-continued droughts destroy the corn in the blade, and mildew destroys it in the ear; and thus agriculture, formerly deemed paramount, has become only of secondary importance. Extensive tracts which never could have yielded a profitable return under the plough, were seen to be capable of supporting numerous flocks and herds, and the attention of the colonists was generally turned to pasture. The native breed of cattle has been supplanted by better breeds, or improved by crosses with them, so that the cattle of Cape Colony would not suffer by a comparison with those of many of the better improved districts of Europe, while the Cape sheep, remarkable only for the ponderousness of their tails, have been very generally supplanted by finer European breeds, and more especially by merinoes. In 1852 there were in the Colony 4,496,000 sheep, which in that year produced 7,773,505 pounds of wool, and the number of goats was 1,093,000. Grain, particularly wheat, is still grown to a considerable extent in the lower districts, and in ordinary years crops both abundant and of good quality are obtained. In the same districts, and also in Cape division, considerable attention is paid to the culture of the vine, which grows freely, but in general is more remarkable for the quantity than for the quality of its produce. It is well known in commerce by the name of Cape wine, but is not in much repute. The only wine of the Colony which has obtained a high reputation is the luscious red wine, which grows in a very limited district south of Cape Town, and is called Constantia, after the celebrated vineyards near the town of that name, where alone it is produced.
Manufactures.—These are limited to a few articles of primary necessity; and for supplies of manufactured articles generally the colonists depend
on the mother country, w'hence they obtain goods of a better quality and at a cheaper rate than they could themselves hope to produce.
Commerce.—The commerce of the Colony is rapidly increasing, and has already become very valuable. The principal exports are wool, wine, skins, hides, ivory, whale-oil, aloes, etc., and the whole in 1850 were valued at $2,628,689. In the same year the imports were valued at $3,981,043, consisting chiefly of British manufactures and colonial produce. The whale fishery, formerly pursued with some degree of activity, has now materially declined.
Government, etc.—In 1853 a new constitution was given to the Colony, and in accordance with its provisions the government has been reorganized. The governor is appointed by the crown. The Parliament consists of a legislative council and a house of assembly—the former is made up of 15 elective members and the chief judge of the Colony, who holds his seat in right of his office and is president whenever present; otherwise the members are for ten years, but eight and seven retire alternately every five years. Five members form a quorum, and all questions are decided by a majority vote, not including that of the president, except the votes are equal. The House of Assembly consists of 46 members elected for five years, and twelve form a quorum. The electors are such male persons, not subject to legal incapacity, who have occupied for 12 months previous to the day of election premises or land of the annual value of c£25, or been in receipt of salary not less than d£50 per annum. Each district returns two members; Grahamstown two, and Cape Town (including the municipality of Green Point) returns four members. A property qualification is required for members of both houses of d£2,000 in real estate or c£4,000 in personal property, clear of all mortgages and debts. The colonial secretary, the treasurer, the attorney-general, and the auditor are empowered ex-officio to act and speak in both houses, but not to vote. A session must be held at least once a year. The governor has power to assent or dissent to bills passed, or to reserve them for the royal pleasure; but the sovereign in council may disallow of acts assented to by the governor. Each province is administered by a lieutenant-governor, and each district by a civil commissioner, subordinate to whom are magistrates superintending tracts of country 15 to 20 miles in circuit. Justice is administered by a supreme court of judicature, presided over by a chief-justice and three puisne judges; a high sheriff and deputy sheriff for each district, a court of vice-admiralty, police and other courts.
Revenue, etc.—The gross revenue of the Colony in 1850 amounted to $1,073,059, the cost of collection being $91,373. The principal sources were—customs $402,182, land revenue $69,600, land sales $41,697, transfer duties $97,857, auction duties $82,833, stamps and licenses $98,912, and postage $45,955. The total military expenditure was $759,365, and thetnumber of men, including the artillery, was 4,790.
Religion and Education.—Public worship in the churches of the several denominations is partly or entirely supported by the government. The Established or English Church is presided over by the bishop of Cape Town, with a dean, four canons, and two archdeacons. The bishop of Cape Town is metropolitan, and has under him the bishop of Grahamstown and the bishop of Natal, and his diocese also includes the island of St. Helena. In 1851 there were in the Colony 147 places of worship, and of these 34 belonged to the Dutch Reformed Church, 23 to the Established Church, 13 to different Presbyterian denominations, 6 to the Roman Catholic Church, 34 to the Wesleyans, 29 to the Independents, 5 to the Moravian Church, and 9 to the Lutheran Church. To each of these were attached Sunday and evening schools. The public provision for education is made on a comprehensive and liberal scale; and in each district town there is a government free school, which is kept independent of sectarian influence. In all, public and private, there are 672 schools. In Cape Town there is the South African College, and in the Cape district a diocesan collegiate school. The government expenditure for school purposes in 1851 amounted to $19,680, and for church support to $77,088.
Towns, Villages, etc.—Cape Town. capital of the Colony, is a fortified town on the south coast, at the foot of Table Mountain, and on the southwest shore of Table Bay. It is regularly laid out in the Dutch style, with canals in the principal streets, and the sides of the principal avenues are lined with oaks, poplars, and pines. The houses are flat.-roofed and either painted or whitewashed, with terraces in front. The view of the town and its vicinity from the bay anchorage is very striking. Behind rise the perpendicular sides of Table Mountain, while on either hand are the barren crags of Lion’s Head and Devil’s Peak, the former usually capped with a cloud. Table Bay is capacious enough to contain any number of vessels, but is exposed to westerly winds, which from June to August produce heavy swells. To the port, at which is the custom-house, large vessels can not come ; but the anchorage in the bay is usually safe, and great efforts are being made to improve it. In the vicinity are numerous villas, and the walks near the town are pretty and well kept; one which leads along the top of Wynbey Hill, overlooking the town and bay, and commanding a view of the sandy plain and distant mountains with Green Point, is peculiarly picturesque. The climate is considered salubrious, and the place is much frequented by Indian residents on leave of absence. Cape Town was founded by the Dutch in 1650. The population in 1848 amounted to 22.543 souls.
Grahamstown, the principal town of the eastern province, is situated near the sources of the Kowie River, on a plateau about 700 feet above the sea. It contains about 6.000 inhabitants. Port Elizabeth, on the
*	%	J
north-west corner of Algoa Bay, is a mean-looking but thriving town of 5,000 inhabitants, and is the principal port of the eastern province. In 1848-9 there entered the port 138 vessels, of 24,900 tons, and the value of exports and imports were $635,813 and $1,566,206 respectively. The anchorage of the bay, though open to the south-east winds, is not unsafe, but the landing is often impracticable, on account of the heavy surf. . Graaf-Reynet. about 500 miles east of Cape Town and 142 miles north-west from Grahamstown, stands on the Sunday River, near the foot of the Great Sneeuw Berjen. It is a pretty-looking town, and inhabited almost exclusively by Dutch. Population 3,000. Uitenhage stands on the Zwartkops River, in a fertile valley surrounded by woode-d hills. It has been proposed to remove the seat of government to this town. Simon's Town) 24 miles from Cape Town, is a small place stretching along the shore of the bay, and backed by steep, barren, stony hills. Simon’s Bay, the station for ships of war. is a cove on the southwest side of False Bay, and is a well-sheltered harbor. Zwellendam, Stellenbosch, and Beaufort, the chief places of the districts so called, are large and flourishing villages.
Historical Sketch.—The Cape of Good Hope was discovered in 1486 by Bartholomew Diaz. In 1620 two commanders of the English East India Company took possession of the country in the name of King James ; but no settlement was then formed. In 1650 it was colonized by the Dutch government, and remained in their possession for 156 years. In 1795 it was taken possession of by a British armament, but restored to the Dutch in 1802. In 1806 it was again taken by the British, and confirmed to them at the general peace in 1814. Almost ever since this period a succession of hostilities has occurred between the colonists and the Kafirs on the east and north-east frontiers of the Colony. An attempt was recently made by the British government to establish a penal settlement at the Cape, which was successfully resisted by the colonists.

C11) Numidia was the fecond part in our divifion of Africa5 and hath on the Weft the Atlantic^ y on the Eaft JEgypt, onthe North Atlas,and the deferts of Lybia on the South. It is called likewife regio daSylifera,from the abundance of Dates: for they feed upon them only *, a people, idolaters, ideots, thieves,murderers,except feme few Arabians that are mingled among them of ingenuous difpofition, and addi&ed much to Poetry. (12) Lybia thethird is limited on the Eaft with	eft-
ward with the Atlantic^,on the North with Numidia,and the , South with terra Nigritarum. It was called Sacra, as much as Defert: for fo it is,and a dry one too, fiich as can afford no water to a traveller fometimes in feven days journy. The inhabitants are much like to the Numidiansfvjt without any Law almoft of Nature. Yet in this place were two of the Sybils, which prophelied of Chrijl, and Arrius the Eeretick.
