(73) Terra Nigritarum, the Land of Negroes is the fourth, and hath on the Weft the Atlantic^on the Eaft JEthiopia fu-perior, on the North Lybiay on the South the Kingdom of Mamgongo in the inferior Ethiopia. It hath the name either from the colour of the people which are black, or from the River Niger, famous as Nilus almoft, for her overflowing, in-fomuch, that they pafs at fome times in Boats through the whole Country. It is full of Gold and Silver, and other commodities: but the inhabitants moft barbarous. They draw their original from Chus, and have entertained all Religions that came in their way. Firft their own, then the Jen?s^ the Mahometans, and fome of them the Chriftian. For the moft part they live not as if reafon guided their actions, Maginus numbers twenty live Provinces of this Country, which have had their feveral Governors. Now it knoweth but four Kings, and thofe are, (1) the King of T^ombulum^ and he is an infinite rich Monarch, hates a Jen? to the death of his fubjed that converfeth with him: keeps a guard of three thoufand Horfe-men beiides Foot. (2) QiBornaum5 where the people have no proper names, no wives peculiar, and therefore no children which they call their own. (3) Of Goaga, who hath no Eftate but from his fubjeds as he fpends it. (4) Gualatum, a poor Country God wot, not worth either Gentry or Laws, or indeed the name of a Kingdom.
(14)	JEthiopia Superior the fifth, and is called likewife the Kingdom of the Abijjines. It is limited on the North with JEgyP*!on the South with the Montes Lunz, on the Eaft with the Red-Sea, and on the Weft with the Kingdom of the Ni-' gers and Manilongo. It is diftind from the JEthiopia fo often mentioned in Scripture: for by all probability that was in another quarter of the World, and reacheth from the Red-Sea to the Perfian Gulf It is governed by one of the mightieft Em* perors in the World : for his power reacheth almoft to each Tropick, and is called by us Presbyter John. He is the only white man amonglt them, and draws his Line from Solomon, and the Queen of the South. His Court refts not long in any one place, but is movable as well for houfing as retinue. For it conlifts of Tents only to the number of fix thoufand, and in-compaffeth in about twelve or thirteen miles. He hath under him feventy Kings, which have their feveral Laws and Cu-ftoms i Among thefe the Province of Vobas hath one, that no man marry till he hath killed twelve Chriftians. The inhabitants of the whole Region are generally bafe and idle: the better fort have themodefty to attire themfelves, though it be but in Lions and Tigers skins. Their Religion is mix'd. Chriftians they have, but yet differ from us > for they circum-cife both feds. Their oath is by the life of their King, whom they never fee but at Chriftmafs, Eafter, and Holy Rood. Their commodities are Oranges, Lemmons, Citrons, Barly, Sugar, Hony, &c.
(15)	JEthiopia inferior the fixt part of Africans on every fide begirt with Sea, except toward the North* that way it is fevered from the Abijjines by the Montes Lunt. The government of this Region is under five free Kings, f 1) Of Aiana^which contains in it two petty Kingdoms oi Adel and Adiayand abounds with Fie(h,Hony,Wax, Gold, Ivory, Corn, very large Sheep.

(1 <5) Atgvpt is the feventh and laft partofthe African Continent, which deferves a larger Tradfc than we can here afford it. But for the prefent be content with a brief Purveys and fa-tisfy your felf more particularly in the many feveral Authors that write her ftory. It hath on the Eaft the Red-Sea, Barhary on the Weft, on the North the Mediterranenm, and JEthiopia Superior on the South. It was firft poffeft by Cham, and therefore called Chemia in their own antick ftories: or at leaf! by Mitzraim his Grand-child, and is fo agreed upon by moft. For plenty it w as called Orbis horreum, yet it had very feldom any rain, but that defedf was fupplied by the River Nilus. The places of note are, Caire and Alexandria. The firft was heretofore Memphis •, fome fay Babylon, whither the Virgin fled to efcape Herod’s tyranny intended to our Saviour i and bluflr not to (hew the very Cave where (he had hid her Babe. In a Defert about four miles diftant ftand the Pyramides, elieemed rightly one of the feven wonders of the World. To the inhabitants of this Country we owe the invention of Aftrology, Phyfick, writing on Paper. Their Kings names were Pharaoh toward the beginning: Now what the Turk pleafeth.
(17) And this is as far as we may travel by Land: it remains that we loofe out into the bordering Seas, and defery what Iflands we can neer thofe parts of Africa which we have here mentioned. And thefe lie either Southward in the JEtbiopkk^Sca, or elfe Weftward in the Atlantickfdccan.
fx8) The JEtbiopick, Iflands are only two. (1) The Iiland of S. Laurence or Magadafar, four thoufand miles in compafs, and the length more than Italy,rich in all commodities almoft that man can ufe. FRICA as it lay neareft the feat of the firfi people, fo queftionlefs it was next inhabited: and therefore requires the fecond place in our Divifion. It is generally agreed upon, that the North parts were poffefi by the Sons of Cham, not long after the confution. And fo indeed the Kingly Prophet in the 78. Pfalmyufeth the Tents of Cham for the Land of Egypt, which is that part of Africa which joyns upon the South-'weft of Afiay and is divided from the Holy-Land but by a fmall Ijlhmus.Give the people their own asking, and they will have the glory of the firlt Inhabitants of the world: and prove it too, both from the temperature of their Air, and fertility of their Soil, which breeds and nourifheth not only Plants and Fruits, but fends forth, of its own vertue, living creatures in fuch fort, as amazeth the beholder. We have a report (if you will believe it) that in a ground near the River Nilus, there have been found Mice half made up, and Nature taken in the very nick, when (he had already wrought life in the fore-parts,head and bread,the hinder joints yet remaining, in the form of earth. Thus I fuppofe they would have Man at firft grow out of their foil, without the immediate hand of God in his Creation. And it hath been the-opinion of fome vain Philofophers,that for this caufe have made the Ethiopians to be the firft people ^ for that there the Sun by his propin-quity3 wrought fooneft upon the moifture of the ground, and made it fit for Mortality to fprout in.
( 2 ) But to leave thefe,without doubt Africa is ofgreat Antiquity,and fo is allowed by all Hiftorians ofcredit.In the year 1566. the people were increafed to an exceeding Multitude, and therefore were inforced to enlarge their bounds upon their neighbouring Countries. For as it was of a moft rare fertility j fo it lay not any long way from, but had free accefs to it by Land from the Garden of our firft Parents.
(• 3 ) In the time of Abraham we have better affurance from the word of God,that it was then a place of fame,and the Inhabitants of fome growth,for they were able to fupply the wrants of the Countries adjoyningby their ftore: and thither went Abraham out of the Land of Canaan, to avoid the great famine Gen. 12. She had then her Princes, Pharaoh and his mighty men, that feared not to relift God, and were afterward made the inftrumentsof his punifhments upon the children of Ifrael: for they kept them in bondage four hundred years, as was foretold to Abraham in the 15 of Genefis.
( 4 ) But this proof of Ancientry concerns not the whole Country, only thofe Regions which lye under the temperate Zone.The reft for a long time after were unknown to our Geographers, held not habitable, indeed beyond Mount Atlas, by reafon of the extream heat. The reports which pafs of it before Ptolemies time were but at randome, and by guefs of fuch as had never failed it round, or fcarfecome within-fight of it, but at a great diftance, and by this means, either out of their own error, or elfe a defire of glory more than they had defer-vedsor perhaps a Travellers trick to cheat the ignorant world, that could not confute their reports,they fpread many idle fables of monftrous people without heads, with their eyes and mouths ih their breafts, maintained to this day by fome Authors of good efteem.But for my part I hold it moft reafonable to credit S. Augujline, who was born and dyed in Africa.Thzt he in his eighth book De Civitate Dei, acknowledged no fuch creatures, or if they be, they be not men or if men,not born of Adam. And our later Difcoveries joyn in with him,that report not (upon their own experience) of any other people than fuch as our {elves are s and yet I fuppofe they have feen more of the Country than ever any heretofore did. For they pafs not now to fail it round once a year, by the Cape of good Hope,to the Eaft-lide of the very Ijihmus towards the Red-fea.

transcription:
ORDNANCE SURVEY MAPS.
THE ORDNANCE GENERAL MAP OF ENGLAND AND WALES,
F. igraved on the scale of 1 inch to a mile, from the Trigonometrical Surveys made by Order of H. M. Government. In 110 Divisions.
Some of the divisions are printed on a single sheet, size 27 inches by 40, plain, 2s.6d.; coloured, 4s. 6d. each. Others, on two or four smaller sheets, plain, Is.; coloured, Is. Gd. each. '3^/'
Each Division can be had conveniently mountedior the Pocket, at the following prices, viz.:—Large Divisions, plain, 4s. 6d.; coloured, 6s. 6d. Divisions of four small sheets, plain, 6s.; coloured, 8s. Cloth Cases, 6d. extra.
An Index Map, defining the contents of each Section, and distin- , guishing the whole sheets from the quarter sheets, may be had on application, or per post for One Stamp.
SCOTLAND.—The 1-inch General Survey is being published, ls.9d. per sheet. Index gratis on application, or per post for One Stamp.
IRELAND. —The 1-inch General. Survey is published, is. per sheet. Index gratis on application, or per post for One Stamp.
TWENTY-FIVE INCH PARISH MAPS*
THE ORDNANCE MAPS OP PARISHES IN ENGLAND, WALES, AND SC0TL4ND,
On the Scale of 1:2,500, or 25#344 inches to a mile, being nearly one
square inch to an acre.
This Scale is sufficiently large to give block Plans of Houses, and Plans of the Gardens and Grounds in which they stand. Estate Maps can he arranged on this scale, and coloured and mounted to order. The size of each sheet is 40 inches by 27, and any sheet can be had separately. Most of them are 2s. 6d. each. Indexes to each Parish, 3d.; or per post Four Penny Stamps.
ORDNANCE SIX-INCII COUNTY MAPS.
The Counties of Cumberland, Durham, Lancaster, Northumberland, Westmoreland, York, Isle of Wight, and Isle of Man.
Portions of Berks, Cornwall, Devon, Dorset, Essex, Flint, Hants, Herts, Kent, Middlesex, Pembroke. Surrey, Part of Scotland, and the whole of Ireland, are published on the scale of 6 inches to one mile. In sheets, 2s. and 2s 6d. each.
For List of the Maps, Plans, and other Publications of the Ordnance Survey of GreatBritain and Ireland, see STANFORD’S ORDNANCE CATALOGUE. Price, Gd.; per post for Seven Stamps,
London: Edward Stanford, 55, Charing Cross, S.W.
AGENT BY APPOINTMENT.

notes: Map of the Middle East and Asia including the East Indies. It features characteristic misconceptions of early 18th century cartography such as New Guinea as a peninsula of the southern continent and Iapon or Niphon [i.e. Japan] having a huge northern island called Land of Iesso [presumably the islands of Hokkaido and Sakhalin]. Relief is shown pictorially.; Cartouche title.; Title cartouche also contains a dedication to Lord Cowper, High Chancellor of Great Britain from 1714-1718.; Imprint on map: Printed for H. Moll over against Devereux Court without Temple Bar; Ino. [i.e. Tho.] Bowles, Print and Mapseller at the Black Horse in Cornhill; and Tho. Bowles, Print and Mapseller next to the Chapter House in St. Paul's Church yard; by Philip Overton, Map and Printseller near St. Dunstans Church, Fleetstreet; and by John King at ye. Globe in ye. Poultry.; Block of text at far right lower side of map indicating that two Jesuit explorers, Paul Clain and Le Gibien, had reported 87 islands found east or south-east of the Philippines but this was not yet confirmed by other explorers.; Prime meridian: Ferro.; Map 3 from: [Untitled atlas] / Herman Moll. London : [H. Moll, T. Bowles, P. Overton?, approximately 1715].
